;; Book of Arcade Games — Chapter 4: Projectiles

(dialect :applies ("motoi" "sakura"))

(chapter
  :book                "Book of Arcade Games"
  :chapter-number      4
  :title               "Projectiles"
  :dialect             "motoi"
  :audience            :kid
  :also-for            :adult
  :content-rating      :G
  :author-lane         "arcade-games-engineer-lane-2026-07-16"
  :training-eligible   #t
  :confidentiality     "public"
  :voice               "sakura-teaching + game-design"
  :book-version        "1.0.0"
  :prose
"A cannon on the ground. An angle you dial in. A power number that
scales your shot. Pull the trigger — an arc rises against the sky,
peaks, and falls back down. If your aim is true, the shell lands on the
target. If not, you turn a small knob and try again.

That is the projectile family. Artillery games. Angry-birds-shape
physics puzzles. Trebuchet toys on the phone in the airport gate. Every
one of them is `phys/kinematics` — the equation of motion for constant
acceleration — with a paint call each frame.

This chapter builds the whole family from one primitive: a cannon that
spawns a ball with initial velocity `(cos angle * power, sin angle *
power)` and lets gravity do the rest. Then we compare the ball's actual
path to the closed-form kinematics equation and prove they agree. Then
we knock over three cans.

---

## 4.1 The cannon

Aim, fire, watch the arc.

```scheme
;; A cannon at the bottom-left. Dial angle with up/down; fire with 'a'.
(define angle-deg 45)          ;; degrees, 0=flat right, 90=straight up
(define power 6)               ;; initial speed of the projectile

(define (cannon)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.3)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (on-frame
   (lambda ()
     (when (input/down? 'up)   (set! angle-deg (min 89 (+ angle-deg 1))))
     (when (input/down? 'down) (set! angle-deg (max  1 (- angle-deg 1))))
     (when (input/pressed? 'a)
       (let* ((rad (* angle-deg (/ 3.14159 180)))
              (vx  (* power (geom/cos rad)))
              (vy  (* -1 power (geom/sin rad)))
              (b   (world/spawn 'shell 30 210)))
         (entity/shape! b 'circle 3)
         (entity/bounce! b 0.4)
         (entity/set-vel! b vx vy)))
     (world/step)
     (paint-clear)
     (paint-cell 'cannon 30 210 20 10)
     ;; Aim line — show where the barrel points.
     (let ((rad (* angle-deg (/ 3.14159 180))))
       (paint-arrow 30 210
                    (+ 30 (* 40 (geom/cos rad)))
                    (- 210 (* 40 (geom/sin rad)))))
     (world/each 'shell
                 (lambda (s)
                   (paint-cell 'shell (entity/x s) (entity/y s) 3 3)))
     (paint-text (string-append \"Angle: \" (number->string angle-deg))
                 10 10))))

(big-bang cannon)
```

Note the sign flip on `vy`. In screen space y grows down, but 'up' on
a real trajectory is y-negative. `(* -1 power (geom/sin rad))` gives us
a launch that goes UP the screen.

Note `let*` versus `let`. `let*` allows each binding to reference the
previous — `vx` uses `rad`, `vy` uses `rad`. Regular `let` binds all
names in parallel and would not let `vx` see `rad`.

Hold 'up' — the aim line rotates skyward. Hit 'a' — a shell fires along
that line. Gravity curves it. It lands somewhere down-range. Play with
`power = 4` (short range) and `power = 10` (over-the-horizon).

---

## 4.2 The range formula

Physics 101: for a projectile launched with speed `v` at angle `a` on
flat ground under gravity `g`, the range is `v*v * sin(2a) / g`.
Maximum range at `a = 45 degrees`. Range zero at 0 or 90.

Let's verify. We spawn a shell, wait for it to land, and measure how far
it went. Then compare to the formula.

```scheme
;; Fire a shell, wait for landing, print actual range vs predicted.
(define (verify-range)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.3)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (let* ((angle-deg 45)
         (power 8)
         (rad (* angle-deg (/ 3.14159 180)))
         (vx  (* power (geom/cos rad)))
         (vy  (* -1 power (geom/sin rad)))
         (b   (world/spawn 'shell 30 210)))
    (entity/shape! b 'circle 3)
    (entity/bounce! b 0)
    (entity/set-vel! b vx vy)
    ;; Step until the shell rests on the floor.
    (let loop ((n 300))
      (world/step)
      (if (and (> n 0) (< (- (cadr (entity/vel b))) 0.05))
          (loop (- n 1))
          (let* ((actual (- (entity/x b) 30))
                 (predicted (/ (* power power
                                  (* 2 (geom/sin rad) (geom/cos rad)))
                               0.3)))
            (display \"Actual: \")    (display actual)   (newline)
            (display \"Predicted: \") (display predicted) (newline))))))

(verify-range)
;; Actual and predicted should agree within a few percent (integration
;; error). If they disagree by more than ~5%, gravity in the runtime
;; differs from what you asked for, and the reference has drifted.
```

We are RUNNING the physics and CHECKING it against the theory. That is
the pedagogical superpower of a physics-first game engine: the code
does not just LOOK physical, it IS. When kids get to trigonometry in
school, they have already touched sin and cos. When they get to
integration, they have already accumulated velocity into position.

---

## 4.3 Draw the trajectory

We can visualize the arc by remembering every position the shell
occupies and painting them all.

```scheme
;; A shell fires; we remember its trail and paint it as a dotted arc.
(define trail '())
(define (trailed-cannon)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.3)
  (world/floor! 220)
  (let* ((rad (* 55 (/ 3.14159 180)))
         (b   (world/spawn 'shell 30 210)))
    (entity/shape! b 'circle 3)
    (entity/bounce! b 0.3)
    (entity/set-vel! b (* 8 (geom/cos rad)) (* -8 (geom/sin rad)))
    (on-frame
     (lambda ()
       (world/step)
       ;; Every 3rd frame, remember the shell's position.
       (when (= (modulo (world/frame) 3) 0)
         (set! trail (cons (list (entity/x b) (entity/y b)) trail)))
       (paint-clear)
       (paint-cell 'cannon 30 210 20 10)
       ;; Paint each trail point as a small dot.
       (for-each (lambda (pt)
                   (paint-cell 'dot (car pt) (cadr pt) 2 2))
                 trail)
       (paint-cell 'shell (entity/x b) (entity/y b) 4 4)))))

(big-bang trailed-cannon)
```

`cons` prepends to the list; the trail grows head-first, most recent
first. We paint every point. The dotted arc appears, curves under
gravity, hits the floor, bounces, arcs lower, and so on. The kid
literally SEES the parabola.

Warning: the trail grows forever. For a real game, cap it —
`(when (> (length trail) 100) (set! trail (take trail 100)))` — to
avoid unbounded memory. Or clear it every fire.

---

## 4.4 Target practice

Now put three cans on the floor. Knock them over.

```scheme
;; Three cans down-range. Hit all three with three shots.
(define angle-deg 60)
(define power 7)
(define shells-fired 0)
(define cans-hit 0)

(define (target-practice)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.3)
  (world/floor! 220)
  ;; Cans as short vertical rects.
  (let ((can1 (world/spawn 'can 200 205))
        (can2 (world/spawn 'can 240 205))
        (can3 (world/spawn 'can 280 205)))
    (for-each (lambda (c)
                (entity/shape! c 'rect 12 30)
                (entity/solid! c #t))
              (list can1 can2 can3)))
  (on-frame
   (lambda ()
     (when (input/down? 'up)   (set! angle-deg (min 89 (+ angle-deg 1))))
     (when (input/down? 'down) (set! angle-deg (max  1 (- angle-deg 1))))
     (when (input/pressed? 'a)
       (set! shells-fired (+ shells-fired 1))
       (let* ((rad (* angle-deg (/ 3.14159 180)))
              (b (world/spawn 'shell 30 210)))
         (entity/shape! b 'circle 3)
         (entity/set-vel! b (* power (geom/cos rad))
                            (* -1 power (geom/sin rad)))))
     (world/step)
     ;; Any (shell, can) collision knocks the can down.
     (for-each
      (lambda (pair)
        (let ((a (car pair)) (b (cadr pair)))
          (cond
            ((and (eq? (entity/kind a) 'shell) (eq? (entity/kind b) 'can))
             (entity/despawn! b) (entity/despawn! a)
             (set! cans-hit (+ cans-hit 1))
             (world/camera-shake! 5 0.9))
            ((and (eq? (entity/kind b) 'shell) (eq? (entity/kind a) 'can))
             (entity/despawn! a) (entity/despawn! b)
             (set! cans-hit (+ cans-hit 1))
             (world/camera-shake! 5 0.9)))))
      (world/collisions))
     (paint-clear)
     (paint-cell 'cannon 30 210 20 10)
     (world/each 'can (lambda (c)
                        (paint-cell 'can (entity/x c) (entity/y c) 12 30)))
     (world/each 'shell (lambda (s)
                          (paint-cell 'shell (entity/x s) (entity/y s) 3 3)))
     (paint-text (string-append \"Fired: \" (number->string shells-fired)
                                \" Hit: \" (number->string cans-hit)) 10 10)
     (when (= cans-hit 3)
       (paint-text \"YOU WIN!\" 120 60)))))

(big-bang target-practice)
```

`world/camera-shake! 5 0.9` shakes the whole screen by 5 pixels max
with 0.9 decay per frame. Impact feedback. Chapter 6 covers this in
depth as FEEL; here we use it because a hit without shake feels
weightless.

`cond` handles the case where the collision-pair list orders the two
entities either way — sometimes shell first, sometimes can first. We
handle both.

---

## 4.5 The four patterns

**Composition.** A projectile is composed: shape, initial velocity,
bounce coefficient, tag (`'shell`). A cannon is composed: aim state
(angle), power state, spawn-position. The target (can) is composed: a
rect shape, solid flag, tag.

**Orchestration.** The frame loop orchestrates poll (angle
adjustment), poll (fire), physics update, collision walk, draw. Fire
happens BEFORE `world/step` so the new shell has a chance to move this
frame — spawning after step means one frame of visual stillness at the
cannon's mouth.

**In-routing.** Angle-adjust routes to a mutation of `angle-deg`; fire
routes to a spawn. Two buttons, two handlers, cleanly separated.

**Routing.** Collision pairs route through the `for-each
world/collisions` walk to handlers per kind-combination. Shell-and-can
routes to despawn-both + shake + increment. If we added shell-and-shell
(bullets deflecting bullets), it would be another `cond` arm.

---

## 4.6 Common desktop tasks

**Balloon-pop unlock.** A shop hides discounts inside virtual
balloons floating across the item page. Customer aims a cannon
(one button = aim, one button = fire) and pops balloons. Each popped
balloon reveals a discount code. Uses this chapter's cannon +
projectile primitives with `entity/sensor!` balloons (so shells pass
through them but register a hit).

**Delivery-arc animation.** After purchase, a small package projectile
arcs from the shop's icon to the shopper's cart icon, following
`phys/kinematics`. The physics IS the delivery-in-progress feedback.
Runs in about 1.5 seconds — enough for the kid to notice and smile.

---

## 4.7 Pitfalls

**Shells fall through the cans.** The can was not `entity/solid! c #t`.
Or the shell's velocity is so high that it tunnels past in one frame.
For high velocities, use `entity/sensor! can #t` and check overlap
manually in `on-frame` via `entity/overlaps?`.

**Cans register two hits.** Your collision walk fires both cond arms.
Add `(entity/alive? b)` guards, or dedupe collision pairs. Appendix I
covers this.

**Range formula disagrees with actual by 20%+.** Integration error.
For visible-scale gravity constants (0.1 to 0.5), the runtime's
integrator is close but not exact. That is fine for a game and honest.
Use the formula for design; use the sim for play.

**Trail memory blows up.** Cap the list length or clear on each fire.

**Cannon fires off-screen.** Check that shell spawn-position (30,
210) is on-screen and below the floor. If you spawn AT the floor line
(220), the shell instantly registers a floor collision.

---

## 4.8 Try this yourself

1. Add wind: `world/wind! 0.05 0`. The shell drifts down-range. Now
   the range formula is wrong; only the sim tells you where to aim.
2. Move the cannon up onto a platform (spawn at y=100). The range
   equation gains a term for launch height. Derive it.
3. Add a moving target — a can that slides left-right via
   `entity/set-vel!`. Now you must lead the shot.
4. Fire multiple shells in a spread: on 'a' press, spawn three shells
   at angles `angle-deg - 5`, `angle-deg`, `angle-deg + 5`. Shotgun.
5. Add a `paint-arrow` from cannon showing PREDICTED landing spot
   (compute range formula each frame). The kid learns aim visually.
6. Turn on `entity/bounce! shell 0.6` and give cans a health value.
   Now each shell may hit multiple cans as it bounces along.

---

## 4.9 What we built

A cannon, a projectile, an arc, a target, and a hit-counter. The
range formula, verified in-sim. The trail visualization. Camera-shake
as feedback.

Next chapter: turn the cannon vertical, put the player at the bottom,
enemies at the top. That is the shoot-em-up, and it is where entity
pooling and collision layers earn their keep.")

